deck: Darth Malgus was a Sith lord during the Great Galactic War thousands of years before the events of Star Wars: The Phantom Menace. His achievements include leading the recapture of Korriban by the Sith Empire and the destruction of the Jedi Temple on Coruscant. He is known throughout the galaxy as a ferocious lightsaber combatant and cunning strategist.
description:
Early life

Darth Malgus, originally born under the name Veradun, was a male Sith Lord during the Old Republic era. At a young age, Veradun was sent to the Sith Academy on Dromund Kaas by his adoptive father who realised his incredible potential when he killed a Twilek slave with the Force.

After his training on Dromund Kaas, Veradun was chosen by Vindican to be his Sith apprentice and adopted the name Malgus.

Around this time he also rescued Eleena Daru, a Twilek slave girl form the planet of Geonosis, who would eventually become his lover.

The recapture of Korriban

Malgus and his master Vindican were part of the recapture of the Sith home world of Korriban in 3681 BBY which sparked the Great Galactic War. During the ensuing fight, Malgus and Vindican encountered the Jedi Battlemaster Kao Cen Darach and his apprentice Satele Shan. The latter could escape with the help of Jace Malcolm, a Republic trooper while Kao Cen Darach fought both Sith at once. The Battlemaster managed to mortally wound Vindican after which Malgus took his fallen masters lightsaber and eventually killed Kao Cen Darach.

After the battle was over, Malgus was walking on the surface of Korriban when he received a Force vision which told him that he would be responsible for the destruction of the Jedi order.

The battle of Alderaan

Years later Malgus was selected to lead a surprise assault on Alderaan, leaving a deathly trail of destruction behind him and successfully concurring the planet. However his victory was short-lived when Havoc Squad, a Republic Special Forces unit, launched a counter attack on the Sith forces. It looked that the Sith empire was winning the battle until Satele Shan, the same Jedi Malgus encountered years ago, arrived and turned the tide of the battle in the Republics favour. She took on Malgus herself but was eventually overmatched by the Sith Lord until Jace Malcolm, commander of Havoc Squad, aided her by using a concussion grenade on both himself and Malgus. This proved to be enough of a distraction for Satele to defeat Malgus.

However Malgus survived his encounter with the Jedi knight but was heavily wounded. During his trip back to his command ship, Malgus sensed a Jedi nearby who hed choose to encounter out of anger for his defeat. He was ambushed by a second Jedi who he killed with Force Choke and afterwards used Force lightning to kill the other Jedi.

The Outer Rim

Eventually Malgus ended up fighting the Republic in the Outer Rim on planets like Ord Radama and Serenno. On his initial attempt to concur the planet Ord Radama with the aid of Darth Venemal was successful but because most of his supplies were granted toward Lord Adraas, they eventually lost the planet back to the Republic.

Following his defeat, he attacked Serenno, a planet that was under Republic control, most notably Jedi Master Ven Zallow. Malgus and his army successfully took over the planet because of their swiftness but Ven Zallow managed to escape.

Afterwards Malgus took back Ord Radama from the Republic, hereby restoring his reputation because of his earlier defeat.

The sacking of Coruscant

28 years after the beginning of the Great Galactic War Darth Malgus led a force to attack the Jedi temple on Coruscant. He entered the temple alongside his lover Eleena Daru when a stolen Republic shuttle with the rest of his group arrived. During the ensuing battle, Malgus killed numerous Jedi and finally engaged Jedi Master Ven Zallow, the only worthy opponent present. After a short but intense duel, Malgus impaled the Jedi with his lightsaber while newly arrived Sith forces stormed the temple.
name: Darth Malgus

deck: Jin Mo-Ri is  the protagonist of The God of High School (G.O.H). He has a carefree, likable personality, and he is very skilled in a South Korean martial arts created by his grandfather Jin Tae-Jin, called Renewal Taekwondo which originates from Northern ITF Taekwondo and the World Taekwondo Federation. He is also skilled in the Nabong Needle Ryu art. Jin Mo-Ri has been revealed to be a god (Monkey King/Sun Wukong).
description:
Current Events

With the defeat of the three princes and the completion of the battle in the Sage realm, Jin's clone, Han Dae-Wi, and Yu Mi-Ra rejoin the G.O.H tournament.

History

Jin Mo-Ri is 17 years old but is believed to be over 600. Jin was given to his adopted grandfather Jin Tae-Jin during his mission in South Korea, after his battle with the clone of the Monkey King. The baby (Mo-Ri) was crystallized and asleep when given to Tae-Jin. A while later, Jin awoke from his sleep in an explosion and immediately clung to Jin Tae-Jin.

The baby Mo-Ri was taken in by Jin Tae-Jin and lived in the mountains with his grandfather. Jin Tae-Jin noticed the young Mo-Ri's interest in Taekwondo after Mo-Ri attempted to immitate his grandfather's movements during training. This was the moment Jin Tae-Jin decided to train the young Jin Mo-Ri. Eight years later Jin is allowed to leave the secluded mountains to attend school and gain experience in interacting with others.

Skills

Jin has been shown to suppress his powers and only releases it when in battle with a strong opponent. Jin's skills were first revealed during The God of High School tournament. While being skilled in the Renewal Taekwondo developed by his adopted grandfather, Jin Mo-Ri is also knowledgeable in a pressure point striking style known as Nabong Needle Ryu. This style was taught to him by Na Bong-Chim, a member of a powerful group known as "The Six." The Nabong Needle Ryu style has also been used by Jin to temporarily unlock his limits even further, allowing him to perform feats such as dodging lightning. With the study of Nabong Needle Ryu style, Jin Mo-Ri has acquired exceptional knowledge of the human anatomy, showing skills such as dislocating bones with minor to no pressure.

Powers and Weapons

Jin Mo-Ri possesses a staff called Ruyi Jingu Bang (which is sometimes referred to as "Yeoi" or "Yeo ui" by Jin Mo-Ri). Jin's staff has the power to grow in length and size according to Jin's will. His staff has been shown to grow from the earth to the moon and kill multiple gods in a single hit. The weight of his staff is unknown but it is known to be so heavy that six people struggle to pull it even on a pulley when it's in its normal size.

Jin Mo-Ri also has the ability to call down lightning using his Thunder cloud "Geun Du Eun." His cloud is large enough to cover a considerably large portion of the earth when viewed from space and can strike unlimitedly according to Jin Mo-Ri's will. This was shown in his battle with Taek Jae-Kal after Taek Jae-Kal had turned into a god by absorbing multiple angels. Jin Mo-Ri has no memories of his past which limits his understanding of all his abilities. He is currently on a quest to reclaim his gourd with the possibility of his memories returning if it is in his possession again.

Sage Realm Arc

As the story continues, Jin Mo-Ri ventures to return his memories. He heads to the Sage Realm and Ore Country a land in which he once resided and ruled in his old life. On his journey he encounters a fake Monkey King that was put in place to substitute him. Jin fights his way through his many encountered enemies but gets trapped in his gourd which he came to recover (It holds his memories).

In Jins absence a massive battle breaks out, as the people of Ore Country and his comrades battle the Nox organization and their bishops. In Jins long absence, he encounters what could be said to be a physical embodiment of his past self. Jin is shown the events that took place in his past and the great wars that took place between the Sage Realm, in which he resided and the Heavenly Realm. Jin is shocked by his very different, wicked personality. The Monkey King he believed he was, was much different than what he encountered.

As the battle raged on, the people of Ore Country and Jins comrades began to be overwhelmed by their opponents, The Heavenly Realm. The joining of the most powerful combatants in the Heavenly Realm, the three Royal Princes turned the battle completely one-sided. As the Royal Princes called down an attack of enormous magnitude to cause the destruction of Ore country and their opponents with it, the dying word of the fake Monkey King, Mihu (It had been revealed that he just wanted to be a better ruler than what Jin had been in his past life) released Jin. Jin proceeds to stop the attack of the Royal Princes with his cloud. Appearing in the attire he wore in his past, revealing he had regained his memories and all his godly power. This marks the beginning of the second Great War.
name: Jin Mo-Ri

deck: An Arkham Asylum inmate that only appeared in a few issues before No Man's Land.
description:
History

During the events of Cataclysm, Samantha and several other Arkham inmates are released by the Joker and proceed to run amok in the asylum. Samantha makes allusions to her previous life, claiming that Greg Roark, a guard the group had taken prisoner, was there when she died. The group of inmates decide to compete in a scary story telling competition where the winner gets to kill Greg. Samantha tells the story of her past life in Salem, where she was accused of being a witch, branded with a pentagram and then burnt at the stake. She claims that she was reincarnated and remembers the face of every man who watched her die. The competition ends with no winner and each inmate laying claim to a different part of Greg; Samantha chose the arms. Order is restored in Arkham before Greg can be killed, and the fate of Samantha is not expanded upon. Greg however is so severely disturbed that he becomes an inmate of Arkham. Samantha is seen again among the Arkham inmates in the three issue Road to No Man's Land story arc Waxman and the Clown, but has a very minor role in the events. She is released from the asylum along with all the other inmates but is not seen in No Man's Land.

Identity Confusion

Witch was one of two new female Arkham Asylum inmates mentioned in a single panel of Batman Villains Secret Files & Origins #1, as was Vox. It was originally not clarified whether the woman with the pentagram on her forehead shown in the panel was Witch or Vox. In her subsequent appearance, Batman: Arkham Asylum -Tales of Madness, it is clarified that Vox is another character, however the woman with the pentagram is only referred to as Samantha not Witch. The cell door she stands in front of reads "Samantha Voz."

In Batman: Shadow of the Bat #80, a female inmate meets with Jeremiah Arkham. The illustration resembles Witch, a caucasian woman with a pentagram on her forehead, but the caption identifies the character as Vox and the dialog mentions "the voices" a disorder Vox suffered from.

deck: Vox was a female Batman Villain mentioned in Secret Files Batman Villains #1 in 1998. She never appeared in the book however, she was merely mentioned but appeared in subsequent issues.
description:
Vox was a female Batman Villain mentioned in Secret Files Batman Villains #1 in 1998. She never appeared in the book however, she was merely mentioned.

Vox's first actual appearance was in Batman: Arkham Asylum -Tales of Madness, which took place during Cataclysm. After the Earthquake, Vox was released from her cell in Arkham Asylum by Joker and Killer Croc and partook in a scary story competition with several other inmates; first prize was getting to kill a guard. During the competition it is revealed that Vox hears voices. Vox tells a story about a young girl named Lisa, presumably Vox as a child, who came from an abusive home and violently attacked her younger brother when the voices in her head told her to. When the competition is over, no winner is declared so each inmate claims a different part of the Guard, with Vox choosing the left leg. Jeremiah Arkham regains control of the asylum but Vox's fate is not detailed. She appears again in the three issue arc Waxman and the Clown; a lead in to the No Man's Land event that explained what happened to the Arkham inmates when Gotham City was abandoned. At the end of the story, Jeremiah Arkham released Vox and the other inmates hoping that they would drift into Gotham which he assumed had been abandoned. Vox, however, was not seen during the events of No Man's Land.
